* Where is the ECB going to go on rates - and what will be the economic impact? They have little left to cut and the economic problems have little to do with the current level of interest rates. * With domestic rates so low, isn't The Fed Pushing on A String?

Again, the economic impact of lowering the fed funds rate is likely to be quite modest. * More trade meetings with China? Really, the DJIA rises by 400 points on "another" Trump tweet? As I have indicated, this is much broader than trade, its about economic hedgemony.

The lines in the sand between the two countries represent both economic and cultural divides. There is too much 'first level thinking' that, at least today, represents a Pavlovian reaction to the news flow (China and the ECB).
At least from my perch there is too little "second level thinking." @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @lizclaman

@realmoney The Contrarian View Always Should Be Considered I fully understand the predominant view that the trend is your friend especially if one has a very short trading horizon -- in an investment landscape dominated by ETFs, machines (and algos) that worship at the altar
